search result summaries are insufficient or when detailed data is needed for analysis.\n- Always include source attribution for all information. This is critical for the final report\'s citations.\n- When presenting information from multiple sources, clearly indicate which source each piece of information comes from.\n- Include images using `![Image Description](image_url)` in a separate section.\n- The included images should **only** be from the information gathered **from the search results or the crawled content**. **Never** include images that are not from the search results or the crawled content.\n- Always use the locale of **en-US** for the output.\n- When time range requirements are specified in the task, strictly adhere to these constraints in your search queries and verify that all information provided falls within the specified time period.', additional_kwargs={}, response_metadata={}, id='94a96375-d082-4933-860d-4083e3092465'), HumanMessage(content="# Research Topic\n\nMirny Ice Station Aviation Incident Research\n\n# Completed Research Steps\n\n## Completed Step 1: Search for Mirny Ice Station Aviation Incident Details\n\n<finding>\n[ERROR] Researcher Agent Error (Content Safety Check)\n\nStep: Search for Mirny Ice Station Aviation Incident Details\n\nThe model refused to process the request due to sensitive content detected in the search results or query. This is a safety mechanism of the AI provider. Please try rephrasing your query or skipping this step.\n</finding>\n\n# Current Step\n\n## Title\n\nVerify Survivor Count from Multiple Sources\n\n## Description\n\nCross-reference multiple aviation accident databases and news sources to verify the exact number of survivors from this specific Mirny Ice Station incident, including official accident reports if available.\n\n## Locale\n\nen-US\n\nIMPORTANT: Your response MUST be written entirely in the language specified in the 'Locale' section above (which is en-US). This applies to all sections of your response, including headers, content, and conclusions.\n\nIMPORTANT: Review the 'Completed Research Steps' above carefully. If the information required for the 'Current Step' has already been gathered in previous steps, DO NOT perform new searches. Instead, synthesize the existing information to answer the current step immediately. Only use tools if you are missing specific critical details.", additional_kwargs={}, response_metadata={}, id='49a280ea-a04f-4190-a9d5-81d05078ee9b'), HumanMessage(content='IMPORTANT: DO NOT include inline citations in the text. Instead, track all sources and include a References section at the end using link reference format. Include an empty line between each citation for better readability. Use this format for each reference:\n- [Source Title](URL)\n\n- [Another Source](URL)', additional_kwargs={}, response_metadata={}, name='system', id='e0473122-3648-42e1-b014-c60594b904a2'), AIMessage(content='', additional_kwargs={'refusal': None}, response_metadata={'token_usage': {'completion_tokens': 176, 'prompt_tokens': 3596, 'total_tokens': 3772, 'completion_tokens_details': {'accepted_prediction_tokens': None, 'audio_tokens': None, 'reasoning_tokens': 133, 'rejected_prediction_tokens': None, 'text_tokens': 176}, 'prompt_tokens_details': {'audio_tokens': None, 'cached_tokens': None, 'text_tokens': 3596}}, 'model_provider': 'openai', 'model_name': 'qwen3.5-plus', 'system_fingerprint': None, 'id': 'chatcmpl-d080eb9a-b480-9ef6-9deb-57d604bc8e53', 'finish_reason': 'tool_calls', 'logprobs': None}, name='researcher', id='lc_run--019c9d7f-8ab8-7193-9c8f-e6b119a5ef0e-0', tool_calls=[{'name': 'common_search', 'args': {'query': 'Mirny Station Antarctica aircraft accident 1960s aviation history'}, 'id': 'call_07513f60bc3d444886532247', 'type': 'tool_call'}], invalid_tool_calls=[], usage_metadata={'input_tokens': 3596, 'output_tokens': 176, 'total_tokens': 3772, 'input_token_details': {}, 'output_token_details': {'reasoning': 133}}), ToolMessage(content=[{'type': 'text', 'text': '# 搜索结果\n标题：Mcmurdo Station Airport (Williams Field / Willy Field)\nURL：https://www.airports-worldwide.com/antarctica/mcmurdo_station_antarctica.php\n站点名称：\n发布时间：\n摘要：\nby Tas50. CC BY 3. 0. |\n1957: Pan American Boeing 377 Stratocruiser makes round trip from Christchurch to McMurdo Sound. First civilian flight to Antarctica. 1960: U. S. Navy WV-2 BuNo 126513 crashes after landing short of the ice runway. 1960: First ski-equipped C-130 Hercules cargo aircraft lands in Antarctica. 1960: Sunspots knock out radio communications for eight days, forcing cancellation of all flights between New Zealand and McMurdo.\n\n---\n\n标题：南极冰跑道的事故\nURL：https://zhidao.baidu.com/question/1863467884560437107.html\n站点名称：百度知道\n发布时间：\n摘要：\n1960年10月31日,美国海军洛克希德EC-121坠毁在试图降落的冰跑道。驾驶员和副驾驶员受伤严重，但其轿拿他船员轻伤或受伤。\n新西兰航空901号班机（TE901）是新西兰航空在1979年11月28日前的一班定期的南极洲陆蔽观光航班，由奥克兰国际机场起飞闭悉搭。新西兰航空于1977年2月开办此航班，一直以麦克唐纳-道格拉斯公司的DC-10-30型飞机营运。1979年11月28日当天，第14班航班在南极洲埃里伯斯火山撞山坠毁，机上237名乘客及20名机员全部罹难。\n\n---\n\n标题：China News(翻译+字幕+讲解):我国首架极地固定翼飞机首航南极完美收官 完成各项测试\nURL：https://m.kekenet.com/broadcast/201605/443143.shtml\n站点名称：\n发布时间：\n摘要：\n第 1 页：听力文本 第 2 页：参考译文 第 3 页：重点讲解\nChina has finished testing a new plane set to help Chinese scientists at the Kunlun Station in Antarctica .\nThe aircraft called  " Xue Ying  601",  or snow hawk ,  can fly for  8.2  hours continuously ,  and has a range of  3,000  kilometers .\nIt\'s the first Chinese plane of its kind to be deployed to the south pole .\nChina\'s Kunlun Station is located in an area called Dome A ,  which is thought to be the coldest place on the Earth\'s surface .\nThe aircraft will be able to fly to every corner of the continent .\n" We know the Antarctic has the most hostile climatic condition on Earth ,  and Dome A has the most hostile climatic conditions in Antarctica .\nUndoubtedly the flight is an initiative in the aviation history of Antarctica ."\n\n---\n\n标题：1979年，一艘南极观光客机像往常一样，飞往南极，可就在乘客们还在欣赏南极的美景时，飞机突然撞上雪山。\nURL：https://m.toutiao.com/w/1737775480363021/\n站点名称：今日头条\n发布时间：\n摘要：\n1979年，一艘南极观光客机像往常一样，飞往南极，可就在乘客们还在欣赏南极的美景时，飞机突然撞上雪山。 ，飞机突然撞上雪山。\n新西兰航空公司的南极航线从1977年开通，飞机从奥克兰机场起飞，至南极大陆赏景，而后当晚返程回机场，开通后从未出过意外。 前的是天空还是山体。\n因此导致了灾难的发生。\n这场事故一共罹难257人，其中有44人的遗体因爆炸燃烧无法辨认，南极的观光航班从此停飞，直到15年后才恢复航班。\n\n---\n\n标题：安东诺夫安-10 / Antonov An-10（第二部分：剩余部分）- 中英 ...\nURL：https://zhuanlan.zhihu.com/p/21656936925\n站点名称：\n发布时间：\n摘要：\nOn 8 August 1968, an Aeroflot An-10A (CCCP-11172) crashed on landing at Mirny Airport after the left main landing gear fell off while the landing gear was lowered; there were no casualties.[11]【参考译文】1968年8月8日，苏联航空公司的一架An-10A飞机（注册号为CCCP-11172）在米尔内机场着陆时，起落架放下过程中左主起落架脱落，导致飞机坠毁，但无人员伤亡。[11]\nOn 12 October 1969, an Aeroflot An-10 (CCCP-11169) ran into a trench after landing on a snow-covered runway at Mirny Airport; no casualties.[12]【参考译文】1969年10月12日，苏联航空公司的一架An-10飞机（注册号为CCCP-11169）在米尔内机场一条被雪覆盖的跑道上着陆后，冲入了一个沟壑，但无人员伤亡。[12]\nOn 15 May 1970, an Aeroflot An-10 (CCCP-11149) lost control and crashed at Kishinev (nowChișinău) while performing a two-engined go-around during a training flight, killing the 11 crew.[13]【参考译文】1970年5月15日，苏联航空公司的一架An-10飞机（注册号为CCCP-11149）在执行训练飞行期间，在进行双发复飞时失去控制，在基希讷乌（现称奇西瑙）坠毁，导致机上11名机组人员全部yu4难。[13]', 'id': 'lc_9b3bc9c3-7193-49e2-9607-b49e4bce75d2'}], name='common_search', id='5cf1ce32-34d0-4655-9390-12876391648f', tool_call_id='call_07513f60bc3d444886532247'), AIMessage(content='', additional_kwargs={'refusal': None}, response_metadata={'token_usage': {'completion_tokens': 233, 'prompt_tokens': 5008, 'total_tokens': 5241, 'completion_tokens_details': {'accepted_prediction_tokens': None, 'audio_tokens': None, 'reasoning_tokens': 191, 'rejected_prediction_tokens': None, 'text_tokens': 233}, 'prompt_tokens_details': {'audio_tokens': None, 'cached_tokens': None, 'text_tokens': 5008}}, 'model_provider': 'openai', 'model_name': 'qwen3.5-plus', 'system_fingerprint': None, 'id': 'chatcmpl-0202b22d-39e9-9f7f-a97a-bfaedeb0c22c', 'finish_reason': 'tool_calls', 'logprobs': None}, name='researcher', id='lc_run--019c9d7f-a049-72f3-b678-10392cbd2031-0', tool_calls=[{'name': 'common_search', 'args': {'query': 'Mirny Station aircraft fire refueling accident runway cones stall tailwind'}, 'id': 'call_c3062a5e81a246bc9c1ae42d', 'type': 'tool_call'}], invalid_tool_calls=[], usage_metadata={'input_tokens': 5008, 'output_tokens': 233, 'total_tokens': 5241, 'input_token_details': {}, 'output_token_details': {'reasoning': 191}}), ToolMessage(content=[{'type': 'text', 'text': "# 搜索结果\n标题：Accident\nURL：https://aviation-safety.net/wikibase/wiki.php?id=187927\n站点名称：Aviation Safety Network\n发布时间：\n摘要：\nLocation: Islay-Glenegedale Airport (ILY/EGPI) -  United Kingdom\nPhase:  Landing\nNature: Military\nDeparture airport: Aberdeen Airport (ABZ/EGPD)\nDestination airport: Islay-Glenegedale Airport (ILY/EGPI), United Kingdom\nNarrative:\nA BAe-146-100, operated by the Queens Flight, was substantially damaged when it was involved in an accident at Islay-Glenegedale Airport (ILY/EGPI), United Kingdom. There were no injuries. \nThe landing was on Runway 13, which had an LDA of 1,245 m. The wind was 250° at 20 kt, giving a tailwind component of 12 kt. The approach was unstable, being above the normal approach path and too fast. The aircraft’s speed across the threshold was Vref +32 kt and it landed long, with only 784 m of the runway remaining. The aircraft touched down on its nose landing gear, and ‘wheelbarrowed’, delaying the activation of the weight-on-wheels switches and hence the deployment of the lift spoilers and the selection of ground idle power. The weight-on-wheels switches activated with 509 m of the runway remaining. The aircraft ran off the end of the runway and was damaged. \nIt is understood that the wheel brakes were then applied 'before the full activation of the anti-skid protection systems' causing both inboard main wheels to lock and the subsequent failure of their tyres. There were no reported injuries. It is understood that the pilot handling the aircraft at the time of the accident was HRH The Prince of Wales who was attending a series of engagements in the Hebridean Islands. \nThe flight had come from Aberdeen. Runway 13/31 at Islay is 1,545 metres long with a landing distance available of 1,245 metres. The runway has a tarmac surface. It is reported that the Board of Inquiry found the captain 'negligent' in that '(he failed) to intervene when the aircraft performance and limitations were exceeded in the final stages of the flight'. \nThe navigator was also apparently found 'negligent' for 'failing to advise the captain of the tailwind component and to draw his attention to the inaccurate approach parameters.'\n\n---\n\n标题：美国一机场工人操作失误致高压燃油管脱落 眼瞅航油白白喷射1分钟\nURL：https://mip.wishdown.com/article/467216.html\n站点名称：心愿游戏\n发布时间：\n摘要：\n10月14日消息，这绝对是今年最离谱的意外事件之一了。\n当地时间本月11日，美国航空（AA）旗下美鹰航空（American Eagle）的一架CRJ-900 支线客机在机场加油时突发意外。 机场加油时突发意外。\n由于地勤人员操作失误，致高压燃油管脱落，大量燃油从管口喷涌而出， 喷射压力大，甚至导致管路在地面上不停扭动，仿佛有生命一般。 发已经过去了1分钟。\n更然让人疑惑的是， 事发时其实在飞机尾部有另一名地勤在现场，且显然注意到了异常，然而他却秉持“事不关己高高挂起”的原则，选择了看戏，导致大量航油白白浪费， 可能这就是美国人的松弛吧。", 'id': 'lc_ce740f13-67fa-41e2-9cc0-69e44dbcee09'}], name='common_search', id='78447b0f-7aa9-4123-ac66-0e8847f8dc71', tool_call_id='call_c3062a5e81a246bc9c1ae42d'), AIMessage(content='', additional_kwargs={'refusal': None}, response_metadata={'token_usage': {'completion_tokens': 138, 'prompt_tokens': 5832, 'total_tokens': 5970, 'completion_tokens_details': {'accepted_prediction_tokens': None, 'audio_tokens': None, 'reasoning_tokens': 98, 'rejected_prediction_tokens': None, 'text_tokens': 138}, 'prompt_tokens_details': {'audio_tokens': None, 'cached_tokens': None, 'text_tokens': 5832}}, 'model_provider': 'openai', 'model_name': 'qwen3.5-plus', 'system_fingerprint': None, 'id': 'chatcmpl-1b71058d-d37b-938f-a778-d4604540f3b1', 'finish_reason': 'tool_calls', 'logprobs': None}, name='researcher', id='lc_run--019c9d7f-b839-71a1-b6a6-89821d2026a0-0', tool_calls=[{'name': 'academic_search', 'args': {'__arg1': 'Mirny Station Antarctica aviation accident fire refueling'}, 'id': 'call_36395473eb1f43e3b845f5a4', 'type': 'tool_call'}], invalid_tool_calls=[], usage_metadata={'input_tokens': 5832, 'output_tokens': 138, 'total_tokens': 5970, 'input_token_details': {}, 'output_token_details': {'reasoning': 98}}), ToolMessage(content='Published: 2008-11-13\nTitle: Markov switching negative binomial models: an application to vehicle accident frequencies\nAuthors: Nataliya V. Malyshkina, Fred L. Mannering, Andrew P. Tarko\nSummary: In this paper, two-state Markov switching models are proposed to study accident frequencies. These models assume that there are two unobserved states of roadway safety, and that roadway entities (roadway segments) can switch between these states over time. The states are distinct, in the sense that in the different states accident frequencies are generated by separate counting processes (by separate Poisson or negative binomial processes). To demonstrate the applicability of the approach presented herein, two-state Markov switching negative binomial models are estimated using five-year accident frequencies on Indiana interstate highway segments. Bayesian inference methods and Markov Chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) simulations are used for model estimation. The estimated Markov switching models result in a superior statistical fit relative to the standard (single-state) negative binomial model. It is found that the more frequent state is safer and it is correlated with better weather conditions. The less frequent state is found to be less safe and to be correlated with adverse weather conditions.\n\nPublished: 2014-10-25\nTitle: Data Assimilation of Satellite Fire Detection in Coupled Atmosphere-Fire Simulation by WRF-SFIRE\nAuthors: Jan Mandel, Adam K. Kochanski, Martin Vejmelka, Jonathan D. Beezley\nSummary: Currently available satellite active fire detection products from the VIIRS and MODIS instruments on polar-orbiting satellites produce detection squares in arbitrary locations. There is no global fire/no fire map, no detection under cloud cover, false negatives are common, and the detection squares are much coarser than the resolution of a fire behavior model. Consequently, current active fire satellite detection products should be used to improve fire modeling in a statistical sense only, rather than as a direct input. We describe a new data assimilation method for active fire detection, based on a modification of the fire arrival time to simultaneously minimize the difference from the forecast fire arrival time and maximize the likelihood of the fire detection data. This method is inspired by contour detection methods used in computer vision, and it can be cast as a Bayesian inverse problem technique, or a generalized Tikhonov regularization. After the new fire arrival time on the whole simulation domain is found, the model can be re-run from a time in the past using the new fire arrival time to generate the heat fluxes and to spin up the atmospheric model until the satellite overpass time, when the coupled simulation continues from the modified state.\n\nPublished: 2010-07-13\nTitle: Astronomy in Antarctica\nAuthors: Michael G. Burton\nSummary: Antarctica provides a unique environment for astronomy. The cold, dry and stable air found above the high plateau, as well as the pure ice below, offers new opportunities across the photon & particle spectrum. The summits of the plateau provide the best seeing conditions, the darkest skies and the most transparent atmosphere of any earth-based observing site. Astronomical activities are now underway at four plateau sites: the Amundsen-Scott South Pole Station, Concordia Station at Dome C, Kunlun Station at Dome A and Fuji Station at Dome F, in addition to long duration ballooning from the coastal station of McMurdo. Astronomy conducted includes optical, IR, THz & sub-mm, measurements of the CMBR, solar, as well as high energy astrophysics involving measurement of cosmic rays, gamma rays and neutrinos. Antarctica is also the richest source of meteorites on our planet. An extensive range of site testing measurements have been made over the high plateau. We summarise the facets of Antarctica that are driving developments in astronomy, and review the results of the site testing experiments undertaken to qua', name='academic_search', id='da2b97c8-260b-4fbe-b4fe-ed04870e43ea', tool_call_id='call_36395473eb1f43e3b845f5a4'), AIMessage(content='', additional_kwargs={'refusal': None}, response_metadata={'token_usage': {'completion_tokens': 35, 'prompt_tokens': 6688, 'total_tokens': 6723, 'completion_tokens_details': {'accepted_prediction_tokens': None, 'audio_tokens': None, 'reasoning_tokens': 0, 'rejected_prediction_tokens': None, 'text_tokens': 35}, 'prompt_tokens_details': {'audio_tokens': None, 'cached_tokens': None, 'text_tokens': 6688}}, 'model_provider': 'openai', 'model_name': 'qwen3.5-plus', 'system_fingerprint': None, 'id': 'chatcmpl-202d47a2-8cd0-9883-b3a9-54881f50ca31', 'finish_reason': 'tool_calls', 'logprobs': None}, name='researcher', id='lc_run--019c9d7f-ccd2-7fd0-9d49-b5f1e5dcb3a1-0', tool_calls=[{'name': 'wikipedia', 'args': {'__arg1': 'Mirny Station Antarctica aviation accidents'}, 'id': 'call_7362b7a87b0b4b0daa7c1efa', 'type': 'tool_call'}], invalid_tool_calls=[], usage_metadata={'input_tokens': 6688, 'output_tokens': 35, 'total_tokens': 6723, 'input_token_details': {}, 'output_token_details': {'reasoning': 0}}), ToolMessage(content='Link: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_disasters_in_Antarctica_by_death_toll\n\nPage: List of disasters in Antarctica by death toll\nSummary: The following is a list of known disasters in Antarctica which have resulted in fatalities. It includes disasters which happened on land, as well as in the waters surrounding the continent.\n\nPage: McMurdo Station\nSummary: McMurdo Station is an American Antarctic research station on the southern tip of Ross Island. It is operated by the United States through the United States Antarctic Program (USAP), a branch of the National Science Foundation (NSF). The station is the largest community in Antarctica, capable of supporting up to 1,200 residents, though the population fluctuates seasonally; during the Antarctic night, there are fewer than two hundred people. It serves as one of three year-round United States Antarctic science facilities. Personnel and cargo going to or coming from Amundsen–Scott South Pole Station usually first pass through McMurdo, either by flight or by the McMurdo to South Pole Traverse; it is a hub for activities and science projects in Antarctica. McMurdo, Amundsen-Scott, and Palmer are the three non-seasonal United States stations on the continent, though by the Antarctic Treaty System the bases are not a legal claim (though the right is not forfeited); they are dedicated to scientific research. New Zealand\'s Scott Base is nearby on Hut Point Peninsula, as is Arrival Heights Laboratory. On the base is a heliport, and across the channel is a helicopter refueling station at Marble Point, but the main airfields in the 2020s are Phoenix Airfield and Williams Field which are to the south and built on ice. Winter Quarters Bay is the base seaport, though access can be limited by weather conditions when the sea ice forms. Weather can make it too hard to land aircraft, and an icebreaker may be needed to reach the port facility. However, the sea ice also makes it possible to make ice traverses and travel directly across the bay, and historically an Ice Runway was crafted. The base is powered by a mixture of generators and wind power, though it had a nuclear reactor in the 1960s.\nThe base was first established in the mid-1950s as part of an international program to study and explore Antarctica for peaceful purposes. Daylight is seasonal at McMurdo, corresponding to the south polar summer, and the polar night, which is also winter, lasts from about April to September. As it warms, the sea ice melts, and the port is opened, but by about February, much of the activity drops with plunging temperatures and increasing darkness, and there are usually no flights in or out until July or August.\nThe base has many buildings and staff which support the local population and its many field stations and research projects. The base is the starting point for the South Pole Traverse snow and ice road, which must be cleared each year, as do the snow and ice runways. The base is distant from New Zealand, about the same distance as between New York and Los Angeles, or as between Los Angeles and Hawaii. Some of the projects and/or field stations McMurdo Station has supported include the Lower Erebus Hut, for the study of Mount Erebus (an active volcano to the north of the base), WAIS Divide Camp (an ice coring project), ANDRILL (ANtarctic DRILLing Project), ANSMET (meteorite collection), and the Long Duration Balloon site. Telecommunication sites include Ross Island Earth Station, Black Island Earth Station, and the NASA Ground Station. The Amundsen–Scott South Pole Station is supported primarily through the McMurdo Station, and resources to many international camps also come through McMurdo and its facilities.\n\n\n\nPage: History of Antarctica\nSummary: The history of Antarctica emerges from early Western theories of a vast continent, known as Terra Australis, believed to exist in the far south of the globe. The term Antarctic, referring to the opposite of the Arctic Circle, was coined by Marinus of Tyre in the 2nd century AD.\nThe rounding of the Cape of Good Hope and Cape Horn in\n\n--- [Automatic Crawl of Top Result: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_disasters_in_Antarctica_by_death_toll] ---\nTitle: List of disasters in Antarctica by death toll\n\nURL Source: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_disasters_in_Antarctica_by_death_toll\n\nPublished Time: 2012-03-11T17:06:49Z\n\nMarkdown Content:\nFrom Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia\n\nThe following is a list of known disasters in [Antarctica](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antarctica "Antarctica") which have resulted in fatalities. It includes disasters which happened on land, as well as in the waters surrounding the continent.\n\n| Year | Type | Fatalities | Incident | Location | Comments |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| 1819 | [Shipwreck](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shipwreck "Shipwreck") | 644 | [_San Telmo_ (Spanish ship)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/San_Telmo_(Spanish_ship) "San Telmo (Spanish ship)")[[1]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_disasters_in_Antarctica_by_death_toll#cite_note-SanTelmo-1) | [Drake Passage](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Drake_Passage "Drake Passage"), [Southern Ocean](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Southern_Ocean "Southern Ocean") |  |\n| 1979 | [Aircraft](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aircraft "Aircraft") | 257 | [Air New Zealand Flight 901](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Air_New_Zealand_Flight_901 "Air New Zealand Flight 901")[[2]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_disasters_in_Antarctica_by_death_toll#cite_note-TheErebusStory-2) | [Mount Erebus](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mount_Erebus "Mount Erebus"), [Ross Island](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ross_Island "Ross Island"),... [truncated]', name='wikipedia', id='c234638c-9790-4d78-abd5-195e716f878a', tool_call_id='call_7362b7a87b0b4b0daa7c1efa'), AIMessage(content='', additional_kwargs={'refusal': None}, response_metadata={'token_usage': {'completion_tokens': 127, 'prompt_tokens': 8083, 'total_tokens': 8210, 'completion_tokens_details': {'accepted_prediction_tokens': None, 'audio_tokens': None, 'reasoning_tokens': 80, 'rejected_prediction_tokens': None, 'text_tokens': 127}, 'prompt_tokens_details': {'audio_tokens': None, 'cached_tokens': None, 'text_tokens': 8083}}, 'model_provider': 'openai', 'model_name': 'qwen3.5-plus', 'system_fingerprint': None, 'id': 'chatcmpl-2deda7d3-6636-9a8c-a937-8864ff8511be', 'finish_reason': 'tool_calls', 'logprobs': None}, name='researcher', id='lc_run--019c9d7f-fc46-70f0-98ea-24417e076fda-0', tool_calls=[{'name': 'common_search', 'args': {'query': 'Soviet aircraft accident Mirny Station Antarctica 1960s fire refueling'}, 'id': 'call_cdf416c746984309b409795b', 'type': 'tool_call'}], invalid_tool_calls=[], usage_metadata={'input_tokens': 8083, 'output_tokens': 127, 'total_tokens': 8210, 'input_token_details': {}, 'output_token_details': {'reasoning': 80}}), ToolMessage(content=[{'type': 'text', 'text': '# 搜索结果\n标题：1992年6月19日，一架苏联民航图-154B-1客机（注册号CCCP-85234）执飞符拉迪沃斯托克—萨马拉的5308次航班，中途在布拉茨克经停加油。但随后...\nURL：https://m.toutiao.com/w/1833639436265484/\n站点名称：今日头条\n发布时间：\n摘要：\n1992年6月19日，一架苏联民航图-154B-1客机（注册号CCCP-85234）执飞符拉迪沃斯托克—萨马拉的5308次航班，中途在布拉茨克经停加油。 但随后的例行维护发现飞机存在技术问题，于是全体乘客被要求离机。 达布拉茨克经停加油。 维护过程中，有10名乘客经过机长许可留在了飞机上，其余120名乘客和机组人员离机前往候机楼休息。 两辆加油车通过软管连接起来，同时为CCCP-85282号机加油。\n\n---\n\n标题：两台引擎吸入冰块全数罢工，记1985年苏联民航7481航班明斯克空难\nURL：https://baijiahao.baidu.com/s?id=1827732514195717018\n站点名称：百家号\n发布时间：\n摘要：\n1985年2月1日早上7点57分，一架苏联民航列宁格勒航空队的图波列夫TU-134A客机在明斯克第二机场（现为明斯克国家机场）完成登机及起飞准备，启动了两台索洛维耶夫D-30-2涡轮风扇发动机，开始滑行离开停机坪。 座位的乘客无一幸免。\n苏联民航总局事故调查委员会与图波列夫设计局的技术团队经过详细现场勘查后，初步确定飞机坠毁并非由于机械故障或机组人员操作失误所致。调查重点转向分析两台引擎同时熄火的原因。\n\n---\n\n标题：140吨燃料奔涌而出，上百名科学家葬身火海，真相30年后曝光\nURL：https://m.sohu.com/a/840408819_121645942/?pvid=000115_3w_a\n站点名称：搜狐\n发布时间：\n摘要：\n究竟是如何发生的呢？ 1960年，苏联准备发射一枚R16洲际导弹。 当时，这枚导弹已经直立在发射场地，做好了发射前准备，但是，研究人员忽然发现，导弹的引擎电路出了些故障。 究人员还在进行抢修。 就在此时，导弹的燃料已经渗透到锅炉部位，第二节引擎忽然被点燃，火焰迅速蔓延，大火点燃了燃料缸，140吨燃料喷涌而出，熊熊烈火将整个发射场吞噬，除了一名发射人员因为抽烟走到场外躲过一劫，其余在场的上百名科学家全部牺牲。\n\n---\n\n标题：一架停飞而且被做成纪念标志的苏联安-12运输机居然也能起火，要不是这张照片，这种事儿简直让人无法相信。但是这确实是千真万确的事实：...\nURL：https://m.toutiao.com/a1743952898630669/\n站点名称：今日头条\n发布时间：\n摘要：\n一架停飞而且被做成纪念标志的苏联安-12运输机居然也能起火，要不是这张照片，这种事儿简直让人无法相信。但是这确实是千真万确的事实：1983年夏，停放在奥克鲁格的一架装饰物安-12运输机突然发生大火，火势从驾驶舱部位发端，彻底烧毁了飞机前部，整个机头被烧掉，所幸由于没有油料，飞机没有彻底烧完。经过调查，发现原来是阳光惹的祸——座舱里遗留的一个玻璃瓶子在强烈阳光照耀下，瓶底成了非常理想的聚光凸透镜，它汇集的光线在焦点部位产生高温，引燃了飞机内的可燃物，结果酿成大火。不知道这只玻璃瓶子是因何被遗留在座舱内，也许是机组人员当年享用伏特加的遗存？这场匪夷所思的大火在物理上验证了凸透镜确实能点火。\n\n---\n\n标题：一架苏联民航的IL62在怀特湾上空遇到了强气流导致右边的整个引擎全部脱落,左边的2号引擎又着火,飞机一直在下降,直到坠毁在怀特机场右边的...\nURL：https://m.douyin.com/share/note/7453665545859255610\n站点名称：抖音\n发布时间：\n摘要：\n一架<em>苏联民航</em>的IL62在怀特湾上空遇到了强气流导致右边的整个引擎全部脱落,左边的2<em>号</em>引擎又着火,<em>飞机</em>一直在下降,直到坠毁在怀特机场右边的山上（注册<em>号</em>RA-2345）（编号<em>苏联民航</em>9662）（时间12月28日上午9点）(坠毁地点在怀特山)-博丽灵梦机长于20241229发布在抖音，已经收获了8965个喜欢，来抖音，记录美好生活！', 'id': 'lc_625d3f77-f666-4474-ac08-81af1b66032f'}], name='common_search', id='970c7887-f8ff-47de-976e-f50437ed8b74', tool_call_id='call_cdf416c746984309b409795b'), AIMessage(content='', additional_kwargs={'refusal': None}, response_metadata={'token_usage': {'completion_tokens': 43, 'prompt_tokens': 9338, 'total_tokens': 9381, 'completion_tokens_details': {'accepted_prediction_tokens': None, 'audio_tokens': None, 'reasoning_tokens': 0, 'rejected_prediction_tokens': None, 'text_tokens': 43}, 'prompt_tokens_details': {'audio_tokens': None, 'cached_tokens': None, 'text_tokens': 9338}}, 'model_provider': 'openai', 'model_name': 'qwen3.5-plus', 'system_fingerprint': None, 'id': 'chatcmpl-0ee59804-d9c9-9753-b542-39bd76f2120a', 'finish_reason': 'tool_calls', 'logprobs': None}, name='researcher', id='lc_run--019c9d80-13ad-7ae1-99c0-86b39a729f3c-0', tool_calls=[{'name': 'common_search', 'args': {'query': '"Mirny" "An-10" fire refueling Antarctica accident'}, 'id': 'call_750ea1f127914a1285990e12', 'type': 'tool_call'}], invalid_tool_calls=[], usage_metadata={'input_tokens': 9338, 'output_tokens': 43, 'total_tokens': 9381, 'input_token_details': {}, 'output_token_details': {'reasoning': 0}}), ToolMessage(content="SYSTEM ALERT: You have used the tool 'common_search' 3 times, which is the limit for a single tool. You MUST switch to a DIFFERENT search tool (e.g., use 'academic_search' or 'web_search' instead of 'common_search'). Using the same tool repeatedly is ineffective. TRY ANOTHER TOOL.", name='common_search', id='ae7297b3-41b8-4936-8cb6-9a6554f96d08', tool_call_id='call_750ea1f127914a1285990e12'), AIMessage(content='', additional_kwargs={'refusal': None}, response_metadata={'token_usage': {'completion_tokens': 50, 'prompt_tokens': 9463, 'total_tokens': 9513, 'completion_tokens_details': {'accepted_prediction_tokens': None, 'audio_tokens': None, 'reasoning_tokens': 0, 'rejected_prediction_tokens': None, 'text_tokens': 50}, 'prompt_tokens_details': {'audio_tokens': None, 'cached_tokens': None, 'text_tokens': 9463}}, 'model_provider': 'openai', 'model_name': 'qwen3.5-plus', 'system_fingerprint': None, 'id': 'chatcmpl-94138c64-af38-90c3-b137-c2738d1f7386', 'finish_reason': 'tool_calls', 'logprobs': None}, name='researcher', id='lc_run--019c9d80-1c23-7952-8cc3-989fbdbfa01f-0', tool_calls=[{'name': 'web_search', 'args': {'query': 'Mirny Station Antarctica aircraft fire refueling accident 1960s 1970s survivor'}, 'id': 'call_b7083fdbb97543aab7ab0e51', 'type': 'tool_call'}], invalid_tool_calls=[], usage_metadata={'input_tokens': 9463, 'output_tokens': 50, 'total_tokens': 9513, 'input_token_details': {}, 'output_token_details': {'reasoning': 0}}), ToolMessage(content='Error: web_search is not a valid tool, try one of [academic_search, wikipedia, common_search, crawl_tool].', name='web_search', id='8d6abd48-81fd-41a6-81c5-7bde5ae80213', tool_call_id='call_b7083fdbb97543aab7ab0e51', status='error'), AIMessage(content='', additional_kwargs={'refusal': None}, response_metadata={'token_usage': {'completion_tokens': 153, 'prompt_tokens': 9552, 'total_tokens': 9705, 'completion_tokens_details': {'accepted_prediction_tokens': None, 'audio_tokens': None, 'reasoning_tokens': 114, 'rejected_prediction_tokens': None, 'text_tokens': 153}, 'prompt_tokens_details': {'audio_tokens': None, 'cached_tokens': None, 'text_tokens': 9552}}, 'model_provider': 'openai', 'model_name': 'qwen3.5-plus', 'system_fingerprint': None, 'id': 'chatcmpl-ea9fb312-8084-9590-9c83-8bdfa8e0a0e1', 'finish_reason': 'tool_calls', 'logprobs': None}, name='researcher', id='lc_run--019c9d80-21c8-7ae2-86ad-90b2261ef652-0', tool_calls=[{'name': 'academic_search', 'args': {'__arg1': 'Mirny Station Antarctica aircraft accident runway fire'}, 'id': 'call_f668d560993641569128bb20', 'type': 'tool_call'}], invalid_tool_calls=[], usage_metadata={'input_tokens': 9552, 'output_tokens': 153, 'total_tokens': 9705, 'input_token_details': {}, 'output_token_details': {'reasoning': 114}}), ToolMessage(content='Published: 2008-11-13\nTitle: Markov switching negative binomial models: an application to vehicle accident frequencies\nAuthors: Nataliya V. Malyshkina, Fred L. Mannering, Andrew P. Tarko\nSummary: In this paper, two-state Markov switching models are proposed to study accident frequencies. These models assume that there are two unobserved states of roadway safety, and that roadway entities (roadway segments) can switch between these states over time. The states are distinct, in the sense that in the different states accident frequencies are generated by separate counting processes (by separate Poisson or negative binomial processes). To demonstrate the applicability of the approach presented herein, two-state Markov switching negative binomial models are estimated using five-year accident frequencies on Indiana interstate highway segments. Bayesian inference methods and Markov Chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) simulations are used for model estimation. The estimated Markov switching models result in a superior statistical fit relative to the standard (single-state) negative binomial model. It is found that the more frequent state is safer and it is correlated with better weather conditions. The less frequent state is found to be less safe and to be correlated with adverse weather conditions.\n\nPublished: 2014-10-25\nTitle: Data Assimilation of Satellite Fire Detection in Coupled Atmosphere-Fire Simulation by WRF-SFIRE\nAuthors: Jan Mandel, Adam K. Kochanski, Martin Vejmelka, Jonathan D. Beezley\nSummary: Currently available satellite active fire detection products from the VIIRS and MODIS instruments on polar-orbiting satellites produce detection squares in arbitrary locations. There is no global fire/no fire map, no detection under cloud cover, false negatives are common, and the detection squares are much coarser than the resolution of a fire behavior model. Consequently, current active fire satellite detection products should be used to improve fire modeling in a statistical sense only, rather than as a direct input. We describe a new data assimilation method for active fire detection, based on a modification of the fire arrival time to simultaneously minimize the difference from the forecast fire arrival time and maximize the likelihood of the fire detection data. This method is inspired by contour detection methods used in computer vision, and it can be cast as a Bayesian inverse problem technique, or a generalized Tikhonov regularization. After the new fire arrival time on the whole simulation domain is found, the model can be re-run from a time in the past using the new fire arrival time to generate the heat fluxes and to spin up the atmospheric model until the satellite overpass time, when the coupled simulation continues from the modified state.\n\nPublished: 2010-07-13\nTitle: Astronomy in Antarctica\nAuthors: Michael G. Burton\nSummary: Antarctica provides a unique environment for astronomy. The cold, dry and stable air found above the high plateau, as well as the pure ice below, offers new opportunities across the photon & particle spectrum. The summits of the plateau provide the best seeing conditions, the darkest skies and the most transparent atmosphere of any earth-based observing site. Astronomical activities are now underway at four plateau sites: the Amundsen-Scott South Pole Station, Concordia Station at Dome C, Kunlun Station at Dome A and Fuji Station at Dome F, in addition to long duration ballooning from the coastal station of McMurdo. Astronomy conducted includes optical, IR, THz & sub-mm, measurements of the CMBR, solar, as well as high energy astrophysics involving measurement of cosmic rays, gamma rays and neutrinos. Antarctica is also the richest source of meteorites on our planet. An extensive range of site testing measurements have been made over the high plateau. We summarise the facets of Antarctica that are driving developments in astronomy, and review the results of the site testing experiments undertaken to qua', name='academic_search', id='771f1cf3-7911-40b5-be44-78adaf2165a1', tool_call_id='call_f668d560993641569128bb20'), AIMessage(content='', additional_kwargs={'refusal': None}, response_metadata={'token_usage': {'completion_tokens': 49, 'prompt_tokens': 10407, 'total_tokens': 10456, 'completion_tokens_details': {'accepted_prediction_tokens': None, 'audio_tokens': None, 'reasoning_tokens': 0, 'rejected_prediction_tokens': None, 'text_tokens': 49}, 'prompt_tokens_details': {'audio_tokens': None, 'cached_tokens': None, 'text_tokens': 10407}}, 'model_provider': 'openai', 'model_name': 'qwen3.5-plus', 'system_fingerprint': None, 'id': 'chatcmpl-ff6004d9-87e9-90a4-a228-116161419947', 'finish_reason': 'tool_calls', 'logprobs': None}, name='researcher', id='lc_run--019c9d80-3819-7510-965a-b05d94321fe5-0', tool_calls=[{'name': 'crawl_tool', 'args': {'__arg1': 'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_disasters_in_Antarctica_by_death_toll'}, 'id': 'call_281a2fe85a49475f8ee70ba6', 'type': 'tool_call'}], invalid_tool_calls=[], usage_metadata={'input_tokens': 10407, 'output_tokens': 49, 'total_tokens': 10456, 'input_token_details': {}, 'output_token_details': {'reasoning': 0}}), ToolMessage(content='Title: List of disasters in Antarctica by death toll\n\nURL Source: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_disasters_in_Antarctica_by_death_toll\n\nPublished Time: 2012-03-11T17:06:49Z\n\nMarkdown Content:\nFrom Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia\n\nThe following is a list of known disasters in [Antarctica](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antarctica "Antarctica") which have resulted in fatalities. It includes disasters which happened on land, as well as in the waters surrounding 