nThe Aviation Safety Network and other aviation accident databases that were searched did not return results matching this specific combination of circumstances at Mirny Station.\n\n## Key Findings Summary\n\nThe research identified aircraft incidents at Mirny Station, but none matched the complete description provided. The incidents that were found (1968 and 1969 An-10 accidents) resulted in no fatalities. The 1960 fire incident with 8 fatalities was a building fire, not an aircraft accident.\n\n# Conclusion\n\nBased on the available research, I cannot definitively identify the specific incident described in the question with all the mentioned details (waterlogged runway, tailwind, runway cones, stall, and fire during refueling at Mirny Station). The aircraft incidents found at Mirny Station involving Antonov An-10 aircraft in 1968 and 1969 resulted in **0 fatalities** (all occupants survived), but these incidents do not match all the specific circumstances described.\n\nWithout being able to locate the specific incident matching all the described details, I cannot provide a definitive number of survivors. The research suggests that if this incident occurred, it may not be well-documented in publicly available aviation accident databases or English-language sources.\n\n**Note:** Due to the limitations of the search results and the maximum number of search tool calls reached, I cannot confirm the exact incident or provide a verified survivor count. Additional research through specialized Soviet/Russian aviation accident archives may be required to locate this specific incident.\n\n# References\n\n- [List of disasters in Antarctica by death toll](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_disasters_in_Antarctica_by_death_toll)\n\n- [Research stations in Antarctica](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Research_stations_in_Antarctica)\n\n- [Mirny Station](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mirny_Station)\n\n- [Antonov An-10 accident history (via Zhihu)](https://zhuanlan.zhihu.com/p/21